; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; The focus can be on a physical object perceived thr=\r\nough senses (e.g. an idol or the physical sound of a mantra) or a subtle ob=\r\nject perceived by the subtle perception (a deity or the subtle vibration of=\r\n a mantra). The focus can be on the gross/subtle object or on the act of pe=\r\nrceiving the object or on the perceiver (all the three exist within one&#39;s c=\r\nonsciousness as three different things). One&#39;s self-awareness can identify =\r\nwith one object and focus its attention on another object (&quot;I am Rajarshi w=\r\nith so and so qualities and I am aware of Bhairava with so and so qualities=\r\n&quot;). Or, one&#39;s self-awareness can identify with that object (&quot;I am Bhairava =\r\nwith so and so qualities&quot;). Please note that all these samadhis are within =\r\nthe field of duality. There is still a sense of &quot;this is I&quot; and &quot;this is th=\r\ne rest&quot;, i.e. there is differentiation.&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; * * *&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;=\r\n&gt; The next state is what most people refer to as samadhi. This is a stat=\r\ne where mind is absorbed in non-dual Self, i.e. without any differentiation=\r\n. When there are no notions of &quot;this is I&quot; and &quot;this is the rest&quot;, there ar=\r\ne no thoughts, no opposites and there is only Sat-Chid-Ananda (the bliss of=\r\n just being).&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; * * *&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; Now, let me come to w=\r\nhat Vimalananda says!&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; The non-dual Self is Shiva (or Purus=\r\nha or Narayana). The field of duality is Shakti (or Prakriti or Narayani). =\r\nThough one may normally think that Shiva and Shakti are different, are they=\r\n really different?!&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; Because of our notion that Shiva and S=\r\nhakti are different, we can either be with Shakti or with Shiva at a time b=\r\nut not with both at the same time. A yogi who has objectification and the s=\r\nense of &quot;this is I&quot; and &quot;this is the rest&quot; is in the domain of Shakti. When=\r\n one overcomes objectification and reaches non-dual samadhi, one is in the =\r\ndomain of Shiva. When one leaves that state and one&#39;s egosense (&quot;this is I&quot;=\r\n and &quot;this is the rest&quot;) returns, one will *leave* the domain of Shiva and =\r\nre-enter the field of Shakti. One is prone to be deluded by duality again! =\r\nThat is what Vimalananda is saying.&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; If one can be with Shi=\r\nva *and* Shakti at the *same time*, then one is then not enamored or delude=\r\nd by any aspect of Shakti. When a small aspect of Shakti enamors/deludes on=\r\ne (&quot;this is I&quot;, &quot;that is beautiful&quot;, &quot;that is ugly&quot;, &quot;I like that&quot; etc), on=\r\ne is unable to perceive the entire field of Shakti. This is just like a per=\r\nson tied to a rock in the ocean not being able to swim the entire ocean. Wh=\r\nen one is not bound by any object in the field of Shakti and not attracted =\r\nor repelled by anything, then one can navigate the entire field, i.e. all s=\r\npace-time combinations. This is possible only if one has perfect mastery ov=\r\ner Shakti. That comes only when one has zero attachment to anything in the =\r\nfield of Shakti. That comes only when one is with Shiva enough and eventual=\r\nly becomes like Shiva. If a yogi reaches non-dual samadhi, stays in it for =\r\na long time and happens to come back to the field of duality, then one may =\r\nbecome like Shiva and work with Shakti with zero attachment and perfect mas=\r\ntery. One is aware of the entire field of duality - all spaces and times - =\r\nand yet unattached to anything. That is because one perceives the underlyin=\r\ng non-dual Self even as senses perceive various objects of duality.&lt;BR&gt;&gt;=\r\n &lt;BR&gt;&gt; For most people, this is out of bounds. One either experiences no=\r\nn-dual samadhi for a short duration and cannot sustain it longer and comes =\r\nback to be deluded by duality again, or one stays in non-dual samadhi for a=\r\n long time and does not come back (like a salt doll that goes to survey the=\r\n depth of ocean melting in the ocean, to borrow words from Ramakrishna Para=\r\nmahamsa). Exceptions like Ramakrishna Paramahamsa or Sai Baba, who spent en=\r\nough time in non-dual samadhi and yet came back to live in the world, are s=\r\no rare in this age.&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; * * *&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; Let me put this=\r\n in terms of Kundalini now. When Kundalini is in moolaadhaara, our self-awa=\r\nreness identifies with the physical body and is aware of the physical world=\r\n around us. As Kundalini goes to various places in the subtle body (there a=\r\nre thousands of nadis and chakras!), one is aware of various realities that=\r\n are out there in this universe. For example, one world (realm of awareness=\r\n) may be reverberating with the sound of a particular beejaakshara and fill=\r\ned with a particular light and every being in that world may be a small par=\r\nticle in that light reverberating with that sound. Like that, there are man=\r\ny worlds out there (within us) and one can enter a samadhi through any of t=\r\nhem, when Kundalini reaches a corresponding place.&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; When Ku=\r\nndalini reaches sahasrara, one&#39;s self-awareness is with Shiva. Shakti loses=\r\n herself to Shiva and there is no objectification that is the hallmark of S=\r\nhakti. If shakti comes back from sahasrara to a lower chakra, one&#39;s self-aw=\r\nareness is again deluded by duality. However, if shakti comes back from sah=\r\nasrara to mooladhara *accompanied by* Shiva, then one is aware of duality a=\r\nnd non-dual Self at the same time. One lives as a liberated sage, using the=\r\n body as an instrument to fulfil the will of Nature (since there is no long=\r\ner any individual will).&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; Best regards,&lt;BR&gt;&gt; Narasimha&lt;B=\r\nR&gt;&gt; 